  "prompt": "What is the transpose of a matrix ?",
  "response": "The **transpose of a matrix** is a fundamental operation in linear algebra that involves flipping a matrix over its diagonal. This effectively switches the matrix's rows with its columns.\n\n## Formal Definition\n\nGiven a matrix \\( A \\) with dimensions \\( m \\times n \\) (where \\( m \\) is the number of rows and \\( n \\) is the number of columns), the **transpose** of \\( A \\), denoted as \\( A^T \\) or \\( A' \\), is an \\( n \\times m \\) matrix formed by turning the rows of \\( A \\) into columns and the columns into rows.\n\nMathematically, if:\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\na_{11} & a_{12} & \\dots & a_{1n} \\\\\na_{21} & a_{22} & \\dots & a_{2n} \\\\\n\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\na_{m1} & a_{m2} & \\dots & a_{mn} \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\nThen the transpose of \\( A \\), \\( A^T \\), is:\n\\[\nA^T = \\begin{bmatrix}\na_{11} & a_{21} & \\dots & a_{m1} \\\\\na_{12} & a_{22} & \\dots & a_{m2} \\\\\n\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\na_{1n} & a_{2n} & \\dots & a_{mn} \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\n## Example\n\nConsider the matrix \\( A \\):\n\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 2 & 3 \\\\\n4 & 5 & 6 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\nHere, \\( A \\) is a \\( 2 \\times 3 \\) matrix (2 rows and 3 columns).\n\nThe transpose of \\( A \\), denoted \\( A^T \\), is:\n\n\\[\nA^T = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 4 \\\\\n2 & 5 \\\\\n3 & 6 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\nNow, \\( A^T \\) is a \\( 3 \\times 2 \\) matrix (3 rows and 2 columns).\n\n## Properties of Transposes\n\n1. **Double Transpose**: Taking the transpose twice returns the original matrix.\n   \\[\n   (A^T)^T = A\n   \\]\n\n2. **Addition**: The transpose of a sum of matrices is the sum of their transposes.\n   \\[\n   (A + B)^T = A^T + B^T\n   \\]\n\n3. **Scalar Multiplication**: The transpose of a scalar multiple of a matrix is the scalar multiple of the transpose of the matrix.\n   \\[\n   (cA)^T = cA^T\n   \\]\n   where \\( c \\) is a scalar.\n\n4. **Product**: The transpose of a product of two matrices is the product of their transposes in reverse order.\n   \\[\n   (AB)^T = B^T A^T\n   \\]\n\n5. **Symmetric Matrix**: A matrix \\( A \\) is symmetric if it is equal to its transpose.\n   \\[\n   A = A^T\n   \\]\n\n## Applications\n\n- **Solving Systems of Linear Equations**: Transposes are used in various algorithms for solving linear systems.\n- **Vector Spaces**: Understanding transposes is essential for working with dual spaces and inner products.\n- **Computer Graphics**: Transposes are used in transformations and rotations of objects.\n- **Data Analysis**: In statistics and machine learning, data matrices are often transposed to switch between observations and variables.\n\nUnderstanding the transpose of a matrix is crucial for deeper studies in linear algebra and its applications across different scientific and engineering disciplines.",
